The '''shovel-billed kookaburra''' ('''''Dacelo rex'''''), also known as the '''shovel-billed kingfisher''', is a large, approximately 33&nbsp;cm (13&nbsp;in) long, dark brown [[tree kingfisher]] with a heavy, short, and broad bill that is unique among the [[kingfisher]]s. It has a dark head with a rufous (reddish/brown or rust coloured) stripe behind the eyes, a white throat, a rufous neck collar and underparts, a bright blue rump, brown [[Iris (anatomy)|iris]], brownish-black [[Beak|bill]] with paler mandible (entire bill often appears brownish due to earth), and pale feet. Both sexes are similar in appearance, but are easily recognized from the colour of the tail. The male has a dark bluish tail while female's is rufous. The [[juvenile (organism)|juvenile]] has a female-like [[plumage]] with scale-patterned feathers.<ref name=HBW>{{cite journal |title=Shovel-billed kookaburra |author=P. F. Woodall |year=2020 |journal=Birds of the World |publisher=Cornell Lab of Ornithology |doi=10.2173/bow.shbkoo1.01 |s2cid=225980354 }}</ref>

Formerly considered the sole representative of the [[genus]] ''Clytoceyx'', a [[molecular phylogenetic]] study published in 2017 found that the shovel-billed kookaburra nested with the [[kookaburra|kookaburras]] in the genus ''Dacelo''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Andersen |first1=M.J. |last2=McCullough |first2=J.M. |last3=Mauck III |first3=W.M. |last4=Smith |first4=B.T. |last5=Moyle |first5=R.G. |year=2017 |title=A phylogeny of kingfishers reveals an Indomalayan origin and elevated rates of diversification on oceanic islands |journal=Journal of Biogeography |volume=45 |issue=2 |pages=1–13 |doi=10.1111/jbi.13139 |doi-access=free}} "Early View" version</ref> It was reclassified into ''Dacelo'' by the [[International Ornithologists' Union|International Ornithological Congress]] in 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Rollers, ground rollers, kingfishers – IOC World Bird List |url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/new/bow/rollers/ |access-date=2023-02-03 |website=www.worldbirdnames.org}}</ref>

The shovel-billed kookaburra is [[Endemism in birds|endemic]] to [[New Guinea]]. No subspecies are recognised because the differences in plumage between the races ''imperator'' and ''septentrionalis'' is small.<ref name="BeehlerPratt2016">{{cite book|author1=Bruce M. Beehler|author2=Thane K. Pratt|title=Birds of New Guinea: Distribution, Taxonomy, and Systematics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wRR1CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA226 |year=2016 |publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-8071-3|pages=226–227}}</ref> It primarily occurs in hill forests, but has been recorded from [[sea-level]] up to an altitude of 2400&nbsp;m (7850&nbsp;ft).<ref name="iucn status 11 November 2021" /> The shovel-billed kookaburra finds its food in mud or on moist ground. The diet consists mainly of earthworms, snails, beetles, lizards, and insects. It is inconspicuous and infrequently seen. It is likely that it is partially [[crepuscular]].<ref name="HBW" />

Widespread but uncommon throughout a large part of New Guinea, the shovel-billed kookaburra has a wide range and no special threats have been identified, so the bird is evaluated as being of [[Least Concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]] of Threatened Species.<ref name="iucn status 11 November 2021" />

